<p align="right"><b>November 22, 1998</b>
<p><center><h2>Italy’s Release of Ocalan Sparks Angry Turkish
Reaction</h2></center>
<p>
<P>On 20 of November the court of appeal in Rome overruled a Turkish
warrant for the arrest of the Kurdish guerrilla leader, Abdullah Ocalan,
and freed him from detention. He must stay in Rome because of another arrest
warrant issued by Germany, where he is wanted on charges of incitement
to murder (see <A HREF="det.cfm?id=186">Topic of the Day - November 15,
1998</A>).

<P>Extradition to Turkey was refused partly because Italy's constitution
bars extradition to any country that maintains the death penalty. Turkey
reacted with outrage at the decision, threatening to scale back economic
and military cooperation with Italy. The crisis between the two countries
is likely to come to a head when Italy announces its decision on Ocalan's
bid for political asylum.

<P><B>Source: BBC, Reuters</B>
